<DocsLayout title="Project 5: The multi-user app" description="Build a co-working space portal with authentication, role-based access control, and adversarial testing.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 5: The Multi-User App</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can build a system where different users see different things — and I can't break my own access controls."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">DeskHub — a co-working space portal for Priya's business in Collingwood, Melbourne. Member login, desk and meeting room booking, role-based views (member, admin, owner), and revenue reports. Three types of users, three different dashboards, one system that keeps them all in their lanes.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Authentication, roles, and permissions. For the first time, different users see different things. A member sees their bookings. An admin sees all bookings. An owner sees revenue data. The skill isn't just building it — it's trying to break it.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Adversarial testing becomes the verification method. You're not just checking "does it work?" but "can I access something I shouldn't?" Can a member see another member's bookings by changing the URL? Can someone reach the admin panel by guessing the route? Can a logged-out user hit API endpoints directly?</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Every real multi-user app has access controls. Most access control bugs aren't complex — they're oversights. A forgotten middleware check, an endpoint that doesn't verify the token, a frontend-only guard with no backend enforcement. The skill is systematic verification: testing every boundary, not just the happy path.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "A member can book desks and rooms and view their own bookings — but not anyone else's",
    "A member cannot reach the admin panel or any admin API endpoint",
    "An admin can manage all bookings and members — but cannot see revenue data",
    "An owner can see everything including revenue reports",
    "You've tested every role boundary and can't break your own access controls",
    "Expired tokens, tampered tokens, and missing tokens are all handled correctly",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Implement JWT authentication</li>
    <li>Design role-based access control (member, admin, owner)</li>
    <li>Build different views per role</li>
    <li>Test adversarially — break your own security</li>
    <li>Handle session management and token expiry</li>
    <li>Protect API endpoints, not just UI routes</li>
    <li>Set up a staging/production deployment pipeline</li>
    <li>Implement structured JSON logging</li>
    <li>Enforce test coverage thresholds in CI</li>
    <li>Manage database schema changes with migrations</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/4">Project 4</a> and <a href="/web-dev/checkpoints/after-p4">Checkpoint After Project 4</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">2 weeks. The planning artifacts follow the established pattern. The new dimension — auth, roles, and adversarial testing — adds complexity to implementation and testing.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
